Today, the legendary confectioner is run by the fourth generation of the family that is combining its entrepreneurial skills and new age innovative strategies to scale the heights of their business. In the year 2000, with a Master’s Degree in Commerce, Kedar Chitale joined the family business, and the fourth generation picked up the baton. By this time, Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale was already a name synonymous to the very identity of Maharashtrians and Kedar carried this legacy forward. Until this time, the Chitales sold out whatever they produced through their two outlets in Pune. With new innovations, machinery and automation in their manufacturing plants, the production increased exponentially and with it came the need for marketing and distribution. Rajabhau, Kedar’s grandfather had appointed a manager for marketing and distribution outside Pune, but he decided to assign distribution responsibilities in Pune within the family. Distribution and marketing were new to this business, but Rajabhau took the challenge head-on and recruited Kedar to help him establish the marketing and distribution network in Pune.

As demand for Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale products grew across Pune, Kedar appointed franchisees across Pune in neighbourhoods like Aundh, Baner, Kalyani Nagar, Waraje, Hadapsar, NIBM Road and Nigdi. After the IT boom in Pune and the influx of people from all corners of India who had developed a taste for Chitales' delicacies, he set up small outlets at places like Infosys, Dell, Zencer, TCS and the Eon IT Park. Even the departure lounges at Mumbai and Pune airports opened Chitale outlets and saw an enthusiastic response from the customers. Currently, Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale has 20 Franchises in Pune, outlets in many IT hubs, and five new innovative stores called Chitale Xpress. The products are now also available in 5 continents around the globe and all over the country through the strong distributor and supply chain network developed under his leadership. Kedar Chitale was the first in his generation to shoulder the weight of the Chitale legacy, and paved the way for his brothers to follow.


Indraneel Chitale: Bringing automation to the picture




With a degree in electronic and telecommunications, another fourth-generation Chitale, Indraneel, was trained to be an engineer. However, he discovered his calling was in marketing, product and business development. In 2011, Indraneel formally joined the business and sought a role in product and business development. On the suggestion of his father Sanjay and his uncle Shree, he was assigned the responsibility of manufacturing and production. After training for a year under his father, he went to the Netherlands for training with GEA Group, one of the largest suppliers in the food processing industry. This is where he learnt how machines are conceived, designed, built and commissioned. Upon returning to Pune in 2012, the first project that he undertook and successfully ran was automating the crate washing process. He has special machinery imported from Denmark to wash and dry the crates used for transportation of the products from the factory to the outlets. He then went out to automate the processes for a majority of products manufactured under the Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale banner.

Indraneel has since then taken the task of automating most products that Chitale Bandhu manufacture like Ladoos, Pedhas, Namkeens, Burfis, Katalis, Modaks and the erstwhile Bakarwadi. Along with product automation, Indraneel also focussed on process automation where from procurement to purchase, the entire supply chain is tracked and monitored in an automated environment with data analytics and artificial intelligence helping the brand deliver the freshest product in the shortest amount of time to the customer across 5 states and export markets across the world. Modern techniques like IOT Industry 4.0, Theory of Constraints, Machine Learning etc. are all implemented by Chitale Bandhu under him.

Preparing for the future with excellent hygiene practices: COVID-19 and the road ahead 


In the last few months, the outbreak of the Coronavirus pandemic has transformed business for the food industry in India and across the globe. There is a huge impetus on these companies to reduce the risk of transmission by introducing new protocols on hygiene and safety. At a time like this, Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale has geared up for the new normal by adding a slew of changes in its plants, retail outlets, and distribution systems. The brand started its operations after the lockdown was lifted by adding new protocols to its already strong hygiene practices. Whether it is strict thermal checking at the point of entry, sanitation, heightened social distancing, or educating workers, it is ensuring uncompromised safety. By revising the standard operating procedures at its factory, Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale is also being able to replicate the same at its retail outlets, distribution channels, and online delivery systems. 

Automation has always been a core principle at the brand’s plant, with almost 80% of the products like barfis, ladoos, pedhas, katlis, and Bakarwadi produced in an automated environment. The reliance on automation makes the plant more machine intensive than labour intensive, reducing the chances of contamination during cross handling by a great degree. Thus, the products are manufactured and packaged in a safe environment before being sent out to retail outlets. With no packaging done outside the factory, customers can purchase safe packages at the outlets where workers follow strict hygiene practices by wearing masks, hand gloves, and shields. To limit contact and encourage people to practice social distancing norms, it is also carrying out online delivery of its products across the country. 


Innovation throughout the years



Being a 70-year-old brand, it is necessary to adapt to the changing times if one needs to survive in the market. While keeping in mind the brand legacy, existing consumer base and brand values, Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale is now coming up with some new and unique innovations in products. Innovation in traditional sweets such as Soanpapdi and Modaks by adding flavours to the existing variants has proven to be a great hit among the consumers. Chilli Guava Soanpapdi, Royal Anjeer Soanpapdi, Chatpata Mango Soanpapdi, Blueberry Soanpapdi, Cranberry Soanpapdi, Blueberry Modak, Cranberry Modak, etc. are some of the examples which are widely in demand and are not produced by any other brand.

It is also focusing on handy and pocket-friendly ‘single-serve’ products such as Gulab Jamun, Bakarwadi, a variety of chip-n-dips, Chivadas and Chikki in bar forms, etc. are now either available in the market or are ready to roll out in the near future. These innovations have been done keeping in mind the young audience and their consumption habits and ‘on the go’ lifestyle.

Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale has also found a way to increase the shelf life of the earlier easily perishable mithais without adding harmful artificial preservatives and also maintaining the quality and the original taste that is loved by all. The average shelf life of the mithais is now anywhere between 30-40 days which earlier was around 5-7 days at the most. This has enabled the brand to export their products all over the globe without any fear of spoilage.



Today, Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale’s legacy spans across four generations and the brand is widely recognized for its quality, excellence and superior customer service that has enabled expansion to international markets. It currently exports its diverse range of products to countries across the European Union, USA, South East Asia, Australia, and Dubai. It has always placed customers at the forefront of its innovations and has been working overtime to ensure that they can relish and enjoy its products without any hesitation of the safety element.


